<HL>
   Blood Tests Used
   More Extensively
   For Life Insurance
   ----
   By Karen Slater
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Life-insurance companies are requiring blood samples from
more and more applicants mostly because of the AIDS epidemic.
But the practice has had other effects besides helping
insurers turn away people exposed to the deadly virus.
   The ability to analyze blood for cholesterol levels and
other indicators is one factor that has prompted many
companies to offer lower rates to people judged "preferred"
risks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At the same time, the blood analyses are also leading some
insurers to "rate" -- that is, demand higher premiums from --
a small number of people who wouldn't previously have been
identified as "substandard" risks.
   Around 6% to 8% of applicants are being rated at Lincoln
National Life Insurance Co., up from 5% to 7% before blood
testing was so extensive, says Donald Chambers, chief medical
director at the Fort Wayne, Ind., company. He says the added
ratings mostly reflect findings of impaired liver function,
high cholesterol and previously undetected diabetes.
   Insurers are also postponing action on some applications
until the individuals' doctors can sort out what the abnormal
test readings mean. "We are not going to write the insurance
until the situation is resolved, or at least defined," says
John Snore, vice president for underwriting and claims at
Prudential Insurance Co. of America, Newark, N.J.
   Most insurers are requiring blood samples from people who
seek life-insurance coverage of $100,000 or more. But some
companies have gone down to $50,000, at least in
jurisdictions where the risk of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome looms largest. For instance, Massachusetts Mutual
Life Insurance Co., Springfield, this month dropped to a
$50,000 threshold in California, while holding at $100,000
elsewhere.
   Insurers have also expanded their scrutiny of urine
specimens over the past few years to include tests for
cocaine use. A "surprisingly high" 1% of people tested by
Prudential are showing up as cocaine users and thus are being
turned down for insurance, Mr. Snore says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0139
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0139.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Swiss Apply to Join IMF,
   Mull World Bank Entry
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Switzerland formally applied for membership
in the International Monetary Fund, and is expected to apply
to join the World Bank.
   Switzerland has long had close informal ties with the both
institutions. It is a member of the "Group of 10" industrial
nations, which stands ready to lend to the IMF, when
necessary, to help it provide credit to countries having
international payments difficulties.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, its three major commercial banks frequently
have been underwriters of World Bank debt, and Switzerland
has contributed to various special World Bank accounts. The
country also is a financial backer of the International
Development Association, a World Bank affiliate which
provides interest-free credits to poorer Third World nations.
   Assuming IMF member countries approve the Swiss
application and the country takes the necessary legal steps
to enable it to sign the IMF's articles of agreement, it
could become a member by year end, according to a spokesman
for the 152-nation agency. World Bank officials said a Swiss
request for membership there will be processed as soon as it
is received. Countries seeking to join the World Bank first
must qualify for membership in the IMF.
   The Swiss Federal Council decided "in principle" in 1982
to join the two international agencies, but it temporarily
shelved the idea in 1986 after Swiss voters rejected the
Swiss government's proposal to join the United Nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0138
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0138.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   VPI's Carter Is Renamed
   Quorum Communications
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   U.VPI
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The Carter Organization, which dropped founder
Don Carter earlier this year after he admitted stealing from
clients, now has dropped his name, too.
   Carter, the pre-eminent proxy solicitor of the 1980s,
collecting shareholder votes in some of Wall Street's epic
corporate takeover battles, renamed itself Quorum
Communications. Quorum is owned by VPI Group PLC of Britain,
which bought it from Mr. Carter in 1987 for $75 million. The
Carter Valin Pollin investor relations consulting unit is
being folded in as a Quorum division.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Quorum's chief executive officer, Dennis Mensch, said the
change "should make it clear that we are looking to the
future, rather than relying on the past, to establish our
corporate identity."
   Mr. Carter founded the firm in 1974. His sentencing, which
had been scheduled for yesterday in state court, was
postponed to July 10. He faces a maximum four-year prison
term for grand larceny involving false billing and
overcharging of corporate clients, and for tax evasion. In
London, Angus Maitland, VPI chairman, said Quorum has come
"through a very difficult period. This has tempered the
company" and allowed it to return its focus on serving
blue-chip clients.
   Mr. Mensch said Quorum has cut its staff to 77 from about
100 in early May, when the company said Arthur Ross,
president and co-chief executive, would leave in a few months
as part of a cost-cutting move. The company has been hurt by
the slowdown in corporate merger activity, but Mr. Ross has
reported "almost no client defections."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
