<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   NBC Expects Ad Revenue
   Shortfall of $200 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   GE
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- National Broadcasting Co. said it expects a
shortfall of $200 million in advertising revenue this year
because of a decline in the broadcast network audience and
NBC's own faltering prime time lineup.
   NBC President Robert C. Wright disclosed the expected
shortfall at a meeting with the network's 200-plus affiliates
at NBC's annual convention in Washington, D.C.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., has experienced a
slide in viewership from key demographic groups. The result
was the network had to give advertisers free time, or make
good, when a show failed to deliver the audience size
guaranteed to a sponsor.
   In the past TV season, NBC was off 12% from last year in
women viewers 18 to 49 years old and 14% in men 18 to 49,
according to A.C. Nielsen Co. figures.
   All three major broadcasting networks have been hurt by a
sharp drop in ratings that network officials said is the
result of problems with Nielsen's methods of compiling data.
Nielsen officials insisted there is nothing wrong with its
system, although it has agreed to examine ways of improving
it.
   Although NBC finished the 1989-90 season No. 1 for the
fifth year, its ratings were down 9% from last year. And last
month, CBS Inc.'s TV network finished only one-tenth of a
ratings point behind NBC. May is one of four months each year
that local stations use ratings to determine advertising
rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Your Attack on a Myth
   Repeats Another Myth
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   Your otherwise-excellent May 11 editorial "Real Soldiers,"
which attacks the myth of Soviet "liberation," repeats the
myth of 20 million Soviet civilian deaths during World War II
(your figure of 27 million total deaths less seven million
military deaths, of which almost half were sustained in the
wars of aggression against Poland and Finland, when the
Soviets were allies of the Nazis).
   In his carefully documented book "Stalin's Secret War,"
Nikolai Tolstoy puts the figure of Soviet civilian casualties
attributable to the Germans at about seven million. The
balance was directly or indirectly attributable to Soviet
policies during the Finnish campaign -- compelling the
evacuation of people suspected of pro-German sympathies; NKVD
purges; unprecedented mortality in the greatly swollen camps
of the Gulag, and 2.5 million Soviet refugees handed back to
the Soviets by the Allies in 1945 (Operation Keelhaul).
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Anthony T. Bouscaren
   Professor of Political Science Emeritus
   Le Moyne College
   Fayetteville, N.Y.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0129
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0129.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Those Vietnam Dominoes Keep Falling
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   In regard to "Setting the Vietnam Record Straight,"
editorial page, May 4: Without questioning the honest intent
of Arthur Kobler, W. Gage McAfee and Warren Williams, their
attempt to justify the U.S. invasion of Vietnam by proposing
that the legacy "is profoundly constructive" is redolent of
the immortal phrase, "the patient died, but the operation was
successful."
   The record can never be set straight until participants
and historians forbear making such statements as "it was
devastating . . . but . . . " The inclusion of that awful
word "but" is the standard political justification for
keeping open options for the next conflagration. The honor
and dignity of the 55,000 American servicemen who died in
Vietnam cannot be sustained (or vindicated) by economic
successes. Their lives were much more important.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps the three gentlemen have overlooked the recent
events in Europe where, without bloodshed, an economically
free society has emerged from 45 years of communist
aggression. And we didn't use one napalm bomb.
   Patrick A. Dunn
   Decatur, Ga.
   ---
   I quote Messrs. Kobler, McAfee and Williams, " . . . the
transcending legacy of the U.S. war effort is profoundly
constructive: It is the growing prosperity of the 300 million
people who live in Southeast Asia outside of Indochina and
Burma." Apparently, the domino theory will never die. I
suggest they read Barbara Tuchman's "The March of Folly,"
especially the chapter titled "America Betrays Herself in
Vietnam," and Michael Sheehan's "A Bright and Shining Lie."
They should address themselves to Ms. Tuchman's and Mr.
Sheehan's profoundly disturbing analyses of the domino theory
as the rationale for America's war in Vietnam. As for the
transcending legacy of Vietnam: Why not include the loss --
perhaps forever -- of America's high moral reputation, the
disintegration of authority, widespread drug use and the
crippling of presidential power. This legacy from Vietnam has
had an undoubted and profoundly transcending effect on
America, destructive not constructive.
   Sidney Marks
   Knox, Ind.
   ---
   The U.S. committed three gigantic errors in the Vietnam
War. If we citizens forget them, our leaders may err again.
   1. We had no overall goal or purpose.
   2. Our leaders didn't know, or didn't want to know, how
badly the war was going.
   3. Our troops had so many restrictions placed on them
there was no way they could win.
   Elected and appointed officials who made a mess of things
can never be brought to trial. However, we should remember
our Vietnam debacle -- that we may never repeat it.
   Tony Weissgarber
   Lt. Col., USAF, Retired
   San Antonio, Texas
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Moscow Offers Assurances It Won't Slow
   Emigration of Jews, U.S. Official Says
   ----
   By Robert S. Greenberger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST MDEST FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   TURNBERRY, Scotland -- The Soviet Union assured the U.S.
that it won't impede the emigration of Soviet Jews despite
its public threat last week to do so, according to a senior
U.S. official.
   During a private meeting Tuesday night in Denmark, Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze told Secretary of State
James Baker that Moscow has "no plans to change {its}
approach to emigration," the official said. The Soviets have
allowed virtually unrestricted emigration during the past 18
months, and Mr. Shevardnadze emphasized that Moscow is
"committed" to continuing this policy, the official added.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The clarification helps avoid what could have become a
contentious issue between Washington and Moscow. Messrs.
Baker and Shevardnadze were in Denmark to attend an
international human-rights meeting. The U.S. official briefed
reporters aboard Mr. Baker's plane as it departed for a
meeting here of foreign ministers from members of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, during a news
conference in Washington last Sunday after his summit meeting
with President Bush, threatened to slow or halt the issuance
of exit permits unless Israel promises to stop settling the
Soviet-Jewish refugees in occupied Arab territory. Mr.
Gorbachev said he has been "bombarded" with complaints from
Arab governments about resettlement in the occupied
territories. Mr. Gorbachev's remark produced sharp criticism
in the U.S. and puzzled American officials because he hadn't
said it privately.
   Mr. Shevardnadze explained to Mr. Baker during their
meeting Tuesday that the Soviet president's statement was
meant "to demonstrate that we {the Soviets} would like to
have certain understandings from the Israelis because there's
a problem here as far as we're concerned," according to the
U.S. official's account.
   The Bush administration strongly supports the
unconditional emigration of Soviet Jews. But it, too, has
pressed Israel to bar the refugees from settling in the
occupied territories, saying that their settlement there
would be an obstacle to peace efforts. As the flow of Soviet
Jews to Israel has reached 10,000 a month, Arab governments
have grown increasingly alarmed that the refugees will
displace Palestinians.
   Israel claims that fewer than 1% of Soviet-Jewish refugees
settle in the occupied territories. President Bush disagrees
with this figure, however, because it doesn't include Soviet
Jews who have settled in the outskirts of East Jerusalem,
which Israel occupied after the 1967 Six-Day War. Israel
considers united Jerusalem its capital. Mr. Bush provoked a
storm of protest in Israel earlier this year when he urged
Israel to stop settling refugees in the occupied West Bank
and East Jerusalem.
   The senior American official also said that Mr.
Shevardnadze wasn't certain when the Soviet Union's
parliament, the Supreme Soviet, would approve a pending law
codifying Mr. Gorbachev's open-emigration policy. Earlier
this year, the Soviets had predicted the law would be passed
before the Washington summit. But Mr. Shevardnadze told Mr.
Baker that with the new political freedom in the Soviet
Union, Mr. Gorbachev doesn't control the Supreme Soviet's
legislative calendar. Right now, he said, the parliament's
"whole preoccupation" is with economic reform.
   President Bush signed a trade pact with Mr. Gorbachev at
the summit, but he won't submit it to Congress or grant
Moscow most-favored-nation trade status until the Soviet
emigration law is passed. The Soviet delay in passing the law
takes some pressure off Mr. Bush. Congress is expected to
resist approving a trade agreement until the Soviets lift
their economic embargo of Lithuania and begin talks with its
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
