<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Canada's Dollar Rises as Negotiations
   On Quebec's Status Appear to Progress
   ----
   By John Bader
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA EUROP FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Reports suggesting headway is being made in
negotiations on Canada's constitutional deadlock pushed the
Canadian dollar higher against its U.S. counterpart.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and others taking
part in marathon negotiations on the issue of Quebec
province's constitutional status said federal and provincial
officials had made progress in the discussions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Neither Mr. Mulroney nor other officials who spoke would
divulge details of the private talks in Ottawa, but their
assessment was enough for the market, which bid the Canadian
dollar steadily higher through the North American day. In
late afternoon New York trading, the Canadian dollar was at
85.49 U.S. cents, up from 85.03 U.S. cents late Tuesday.
   In other dealings, the U.S. dollar rose modestly against
the mark and yen, but slipped slightly against the pound.
   Canada's talks are a last-ditch effort by Mr. Mulroney to
win a consensus among Canada's 10 provinces on a proposed
constitutional amendment that would codify French-speaking
Quebec's status as a "distinct society" within Canada.
   New Brunswick, one of three provinces stubbornly holding
out against the amendment, tentatively agreed Monday to
ratify the measure. Newfoundland and Manitoba oppose it on
grounds that a liberal interpretation of the "distinct
society" clause by Quebec might allow Francophone authorities
to dilute the civil rights of Quebec's sizable
English-speaking minority.
   Quebec has said it won't tolerate any changes to the
amendment and will secede from Canada if it isn't passed. All
10 provinces must ratify the measure by June 23 for it to
become law. The talks have been in session for the past four
days.
   Market participants said there will have to be some
results if the Canadian dollar is to avoid a quick
retracement of yesterday's gains. "If there's no news by the
end of the week, no change in position," the Canadian
currency will fall no matter how evident a "friendly tone"
is, said Thomas Benfer, senior marketing representative at
Bank of Montreal in New York.
   In late afternoon New York trading, the U.S. dollar was at
1.6885 marks, up from 1.6850 marks late Tuesday, and at
152.65 yen, up from 152.45 yen. Sterling was at US$1.6875, up
from US$1.6870.
   In Tokyo Thursday, the dollar was trading at 152.45 yen
soon after opening at 152.49 yen; it closed in Tokyo
Wednesday at 152.60 yen. Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was
trading at about 1.6880 marks, down a bit from Wednesday's
Tokyo close of 1.6888 marks.
   The mark was hurt by reports of possible East German labor
unrest in coming days, giving up small gains to the U.S. and
Japanese currencies, participants said.
   News that owners of small independent businesses in East
Germany have asked their employees to strike in protest of
the current terms of unification heightened market concern
that the costs of unification could rise.
   The small-business owners said they feared being squeezed
by the 1-to-1 conversion of East German mark wages and
salaries into West German marks, which will occur at the same
time business accounts are halved by a 2-to-1 exchange rate.
   The squeeze could jeopardize as many as 350,000 jobs, one
business spokesman said. Groups representing the retail,
restaurant and service industries have called for a strike
today in Berlin and a national walkout tomorrow.
   Comments late in the day by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
that he doesn't see underlying deterioration in the U.S.
economy had little effect on the U.S. dollar.
   The U.S. currency rose slightly against the yen, as market
concerns about Japanese inflation and the large amount of
Japanese debt secured by inflated real-estate prices tended
to balance the positive factor of Japan's robust economy,
said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Norwest Corp. in
Minneapolis.
   In Europe, the dollar ended modestly weaker, although
action was thin and largely focused on non-dollar activity.
In Tokyo, a report that U.S. Federal Reserve officials don't
support lower interest rates helped the dollar edge up.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, current-delivery gold
dropped $2.40 to settle at $357.40 an ounce, the lowest close
since July 30, 1986. Estimated volume was a moderate three
million ounces.
   In Hong Kong Thursday, gold was quoted at $456.25 an
ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900607-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900607-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Tokyo Stocks Gain Slightly as Traders Await
   Expiration of June Options, Futures Contracts
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST CANDA EUROP JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyo's Nikkei Index rose softly in light trading with
many participants cautious ahead of today's expiration of
June options and futures contracts.
   Meanwhile, prices in London ended moderate trading near
their intraday lows, as the market failed to muster any
strength for a late-day rally.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Nikkei Index of 225 issues gained 31.88 points to
32953.50. The index slipped 3.75 points Tuesday. But
decliners yesterday outnumbered advancers 498 to 438, while
180 issues were unchanged.
   In early trading in Tokyo Thursday, the Nikkei index was
up 91.32 points to 33044.88.
   Wednesday's volume on the first section was estimated at
600 million shares, up a bit from 567.9 million on Tuesday.
   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues in the first
section, which lost 2.31 points Tuesday, slipped 1.86 points,
or 0.08%, to 2423.07.
   The second section index rose 26.20 points, or 0.65%, to
4039.37. The index added 20.23 points Tuesday. Volume in the
section was estimated at 30.7 million shares, up from 29
million shares Tuesday.
   Because many participants are anticipating a potential
overhang of positions outstanding amid the June options and
futures contract expiration today, market atmosphere was
fairly cautious throughout yesterday, traders said.
   Limited buying in blue chips in the morning was met by
arbitrage selling and profit-taking, while early sentiment
was weak on softer bond and currency markets, traders said.
   But in the afternoon, at least one of the Big Four
Japanese securities firms was seen buying approximately 10
million shares of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, resulting in a
minor rally in shipbuilding shares, according to Masahiko
Tsuyuzaki, chief trader at Tachibana Securities Co.
   Other financial institutions later pursued large-capital
issues -- particularly steel stocks -- although rounds of
profit-taking chipped away at gains, the trader said.
   At the same time, major foreign brokerage houses bought
lightly on programs linked to the Nikkei 225 issues,
observers said.
   Speculative buying also drove up prices on selected
shares, the traders said.
   They added that a late rumor, which began after the close
of cash trading but before the futures closing, boosted
activity somewhat in futures trading.
   An announcement by Narita Airport officials that flights
from Japan to and over the Soviet Union were redirected by
flight-control authorities in Moscow sparked speculation of a
coup in the region. But Narita officials reportedly gave no
explanations, outside of citing flight-traffic problems, to
warrant such a rumor, traders said.
   Mitsubishi Heavy Industries rose 30 yen to 1100 yen (20
cents to $7.21) on trading house buying, while the rest of
the sector also posted healthy gains.
   Mitsui Engineering &amp; Shipbuilding rose 30 yen to 1030 yen,
Hitachi Zosen gained 10 yen to 885 yen, Kawasaki Heavy rose
12 yen to 997 yen, and Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries
rose 30 yen to 1200 yen.
   Auto stocks were also firmer, with Isuzu Motor rising 20
yen to 1090 yen, and Toyota adding 70 yen to 2610 yen.
   Other large-capital issues, including Kawasaki Steel, NKK
and Nippon Steel, advanced.
   On the other hand, high-technology electrical shares ended
lower after battling profit-taking.
   Sony fell 90 yen to 8560 yen, Pioneer slipped 40 yen to
6160 yen, and TDK fell 90 yen to 6610 yen.
   Meanwhile, London opened lower, and continued its downward
slide as profittakers moved in and market makers marked
prices lower. In addition, a poor showing by stock futures
reinforced stocks' downward momentum.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 Share Index fell
21.6 points to 2358.5, after falling as many as 25.6 points.
The day's high was when the index was down 12.7 points.
   Other indexes reflected the trend. The Financial Times 30
Share Index dropped 12.9 points to 1881.
   Volume was a moderate 429 million shares, compared with
618.2 million issues Tuesday.
   In the futures markets, the June FT-SE 100 index contract
closed at 2399, down from Tuesday's close of 2423.
   Share losses were spread across most sectors, with the
largest declines recorded by Bass, down 30 pence to #10.70
(51 cents to $18.05), Lloyds, down 12 pence to 297 pence,
Pearson, down 16 pence to 739 pence, and RMC, down 14 pence
to 691 pence.
   The few companies posting gains included Asda, up 5 pence
to 113.5 pence on unconfirmed rumors of a takeover bid. This
gain helped the sector, with Associated British Foods, up 4
pence at 409 pence, and Grand Metropolitan, up 5 pence to 642
pence.
   Rank rose 5 pence to 836 pence, while Hillsdown was up 6
pence to 265 pence, and STC gained 9 pence to 275 pence.
   Elsewhere, stocks ended lower in Amsterdam, Madrid,
Frankfurt, Milan, Zurich, Stockholm and Paris, and mixed in
Brussels. South African gold stocks closed marginally higher.
   In the Asian and Pacific region, shares closed higher in
Hong Kong and Singapore, and lower in Sydney, Manila,
Wellington and Taipei. Seoul was closed.
                                                                                                       

   Here are price trends on the world's major stock markets,
as calculated by Morgan Stanley Capital International
Perspective, Geneva. To make them directly comparable, each
index is based on the close of 1969 equaling 100. The
percentage change is since year-end.
                                                                                                       

