<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   SHEARSON SPLIT itself into two divisions in the brokerage
firm's latest attempt to revive its sagging fortunes. One
unit, responsible for investment banking and trading, will
resurrect the Lehman Brothers name. The other half will
handle individual investors and money management. The
regrouping in effect recognizes that Shearson's two big
takeovers in the 1980s never really worked.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The credit squeeze facing some businesses isn't affecting
consumers so far. Any slowdown in borrowing by consumers
seems to reflect their caution more than tighter bank lending
policies. Some banks are even soliciting new consumer-loan
business.
   ---
   The federal fund that insures single-family home mortgages
with low down payments will be broke by the end of the
decade, Housing Secretary Kemp said. He called for higher
fees on such mortgages, a prospect bankers said would make it
harder for low-income people to buy homes.
   ---
   Deficit-reduction talks between Congress and the White
House resumed, with both sides jockeying over how to proceed
with fiscal 1991 appropriations in the absence of a final
budget agreement for the year.
   ---
   The Bell companies received a potential setback in their
efforts to combine unregulated operations with their basic
phone businesses. A federal appeals panel overturned an FCC
decision allowing such combinations.
   ---
   Real estate woes could hurt banks in certain areas outside
New England, but the newly identified problems aren't as
great as those in that part of the country, the U.S.
comptroller of the currency said. He refused to disclose the
additional regions.
   ---
   Stock prices declined in a second day of profit-taking.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 2911.65, down
13.35 points, in moderately active trading. The dollar rose
slightly against the mark and the yen.
                                                                                                       

   Junk bonds rallied, even as the Resolution Trust Corp. put
up for sale more than $50 million of bonds held by failed
S&amp;Ls. The price stability may indicate the market is firming.
   ---
   Oil prices rose despite uncertainties about OPEC output
and bearish figures on U.S. petroleum inventories. Some
traders saw a turnaround in the making for the world oil
markets.
   ---
   Moody's lowered its rating on New York state's general
obligation debt, citing the state's financial condition and
the region's economic uncertainty.
   ---
   Salomon beat out nine other investment banks to be adviser
to the U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corp.'s Eastern
European Growth Fund.
   ---
   Small-business earnings rose 6.2% last year, less than the
6.7% and 9.2% increases in the two preceding years.
   ---
   Lands' End's top merchandiser resigned amid criticism of
the catalog firm's product selection. He hinted at
differences with senior executives over product
introductions.
   ---
   Life insurers are increasingly drawing a distinction
between people who are basically healthy and those they
consider "preferred" risks.
   ---
   West Germany's economy grew an inflation-adjusted 2.5% in
the first quarter from the preceding period, and economists
predict the pace will continue through 1990 as firms expand
to rebuild East German industry.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 164,020,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2911.65, off 13.35; transportation 1212.77, up 0.18;
utilities 214.54, off 0.56.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3420.48, up
0.99.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.41, off 0.30;
spot index 133.15, up 0.16.
   Dollar: 152.65 yen, up 0.20; 1.6885 marks, up 0.0035.
</TEXT>
